<protolog id="rid.12545_nm.21405" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.21405" rank="genus">Desertibacter</organism><reference id="rid.12545"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Liu</surname><given-names>M.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Dai</surname><given-names>J.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Liu</surname><given-names>Y.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Cai</surname><given-names>F.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Wang</surname><given-names>Y.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Rahman</surname><given-names>E.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Fang</surname><given-names>C.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Desertibacter roseus gen. nov., sp. nov., a gamma radiation-resistant bacterium in the family Rhodospirillaceae, isolated from desert sand</article-title><year>2011</year><volume>61</volume><issue>5</issue><fpage>1109</fpage><lpage>1113</lpage><source id="117">International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology</source><abbrev>Int J Syst Evol Microbiol</abbrev><issn>1466-5026</issn><essn>1466-5034</essn><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1099/ijs.0.021246-0</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">20543156</pub-id></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <em>Desertibacter</em> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><em>Desertibacter</em> (De.ser.ti.bac′ter. L. n. <em>desertum</em> desert; N.L. masc. n. <em>bacter</em> rod; N.L. masc. n. <em>Desertibacter</em> a desert bacterium).</s></p><p class="description"><s>Cells are Gram-negative rods, motile by means of a single polar flagellum and strictly aerobic.</s><s>Catalase- and oxidase-positive.</s><s>Nitrate is reduced to nitrite.</s><s>Unable to fix nitrogen.</s><s>Bacteriochlorophyll <em>a</em> is not detected.</s><s>The isoprenoid quinone is Q-10.</s><s>The main cellular fatty acids are C<sub>18 : 1</sub>ω7<em>c</em>, C<sub>16 : 0</sub>, C<sub>18 : 0</sub>, summed feature 3 (iso-C<sub>15 : 0</sub> 2-OH and/or C<sub>16 : 1</sub>ω7<em>c</em>) and C<sub>16 : 1</sub>ω5<em>c</em>.</s><s>On the basis of 16S rRNA gene sequence analysis, the genus belongs to the family <em>Rhodospirillaceae</em>.</s><s>The type species is <em>Desertibacter roseus</em>.</s></p></content></protolog>